<DOC><DOCNO> AP890619-0204 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-19-89 0825EST</FILEID><FIRST>a a BC-History Adv26   06-19 0455</FIRST><SECOND>BC-History, Adv 26,0471</SECOND><HEAD>$adv26</HEAD><HEAD>For Release Monday, June 26</HEAD><HEAD>Today In History</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Today is Monday, June 26, the 177th day of 1989. There are 188days left in the year.   Today's highlight in history:   On June 26, 1963, President John F. Kennedy visited West Berlin,where he was greeted by more than 1 million of the divided city'sresidents. In a speech, Kennedy made his famous declaration, ``Ichbin ein Berliner.''   On this date:   In 1870, the first section of Atlantic City, N.J., boardwalk wasopened to the public.   In 1900, a commission that included Dr. Walter Reed began thefight against the deadly disease yellow fever.   In 1917, the first troops of the American Expeditionary Forcearrived in France during World War I.   In 1919, the first issue of the New York Daily News was published.   In 1945, the charter of the United Nations was signed by 50countries in San Francisco. (The text of the charter was in fivelanguages: Chinese, English, French, Russian and Spanish.)   In 1948, in response to the Soviet blockade of West Berlin, theUnited States announced it would increase its daily cargo flights tothe western sector of the isolated German city.   In 1959, President Dwight D. Eisenhower joined Britain's QueenElizabeth II in ceremonies officially opening the St. LawrenceSeaway.   In 1975, citing what she called a ``deep and widespreadconspiracy'' against her government, Indian Prime Minister IndiraGandhi declared a state of emergency.   In 1977, 42 people were killed when a fire, caused by an inmatewho had ignited padding material in his cell, sent toxic smokepouring through the Maury County Jail in Columbia, Tenn.   In 1987, Supreme Court Justice Lewis F. Powell Jr. announced hisretirement from the nation's highest court, leaving a vacancy thatwas eventually filled by Judge Anthony M. Kennedy.   Ten years ago: Heavyweight boxing champion Muhammad Ali confirmedto reporters that he'd sent a letter to the World Boxing Associationresigning his title, saying his third announced retirement wasindeed final.   Five years ago: American Jewish leaders expressed outrage overcomments by Black Muslim leader Louis Farrakhan, who had describedIsrael as an ``outlaw'' nation and seemed to describe Judaism as a``gutter religion'' during a speech in Chicago two days earlier.   One year ago: Three people were killed when a new Airbus jetlinercarrying more than 130 people crashed into a forest during an airshow demonstration flight in Mulhouse, France.   Today's birthdays: Actress Eleanor Parker is 67. Singer BillyDavis is 49.   Thought for today: ``Too bad all the people who know how to runthe country are busy driving taxi cabs and cutting hair.'' _ GeorgeBurns, American comedian (1896- ).</TEXT></DOC>